title: For Sale:  Kahr PM9 DLC 5 mags, leather
postcontent: Reluctantly I'm selling my long time carry gun - due principally to my better hit-abilities with the new baby Glock.  This Kahr PM9 has been carried much/ shot little (660 rounds).  Mind you this premium brand is of a much higher quality than a Glock (fit, finish and materials used) but the facts are what they are and results are what's important to me.  So while many people shoot better with a Double Action gun (like this one) I shoot better with a striker fired Glock.  This version, Model# PM9094, uses drift adjustable, white bar-dot combat sights and has the upgraded DLC treatment; now with complimentary love-hug marks from holster carry (not a concern with a DLC finish).  It comes with 5 OEM magazines (2 x 6 rounds, 3 x 7 rounds) and can be carried in a plus 1 condition.  Additionally this sale includes the original hard case (with all its' original packagings), two extra magazine base plates and two pieces of leather: an outside waist belt carry holster (right hand side) and a separate spare magazine carrier.To see if this gun suits you I'm willing to meet you at the Tristategunclub.net range in Daleville; bring your preferred 9mm ammo (if not a member you'll need to first sign a club waiver).  I generally use cheap 115 gr. FMJ for range training.  For defensive use, with its 3.1" polygonal rifling barrel I load heavier 124 gr. hollow points.  I've previously tested (successfully) loading/firing 147 gr. FMJ ammo.  One more additional feature, this Kahr is rated for +P ammo but as I worried about long term use I have only occassionally shot any; of course it too worked.The only ammo I've found that wasn't reliable came from Freedom Munitions (FM).  FM defensive ammo often hung up chambering the very first round - but if/when it chambered it always went bang, ejected properly and then successfully chambered the following round.  Allow me to modify that, recently I had some Winchester white box (WWB) rounds that were struck but didn't fire (but in fairness, that same box of ammo demonstrated the same problem with another gun); previously my older stock WWB worked fine.The legalese still applies: to purchase this you need an Alabama drivers license, or alternativly be active duty military and stationed in Alabama.  Also a concealed carry permit to make me feel better; without one I'd question - why look at a concealed class of handgun?  Finally ... under those conditions this private sale will incur no FFL fees or sales tax!  Note: without those docs we can still complete this sale thru an FFL dealer, at an additional expense (typically $25). More photos are available; just email your phone and/or email addy and I'll forward them to you.  Same thing for any questions.  As I previously stated, I'm reluctant to see this go but the Glock is now my go to weapon and my safe has only so much room.I'm trying real hard to think of any trades that'd peak my interest - No long guns/shotguns and I already have my glock limit (17,19,43), except for the 34.I would give preference to a quality name full size handgun in 9mm or a flat sided .22 Buckmark w/many magazines + cash.  I'm really pushed for room in the safe and don't need anymore toys.

title: For Sale:  WW2 Obsolete Oklahoma Ordnance Works Aux Military Police Badge
postcontent: Obsolete and rare WW2 era Oklahoma Ordnance Works Auxiliary Military Police Badge.Working saddle pin on reverse.  Includes the wool MP arm band with the badge. Badge measures 2 1/2" by 2 1/4" and has normal wear from use and age.The Oklahoma Ordnance Works (OOW) was a governement-owned, contractor-operated (GOCO) facility that was built in Mayes County, Oklahoma to produce smokeless powder and other military explosives that were to be used during WW2.  The facility was closed form 1946 until 1954, when production resumed until 1956, then closed again.  In 1960, it was sold to the Oklahoma Ordnance Works Authority (OOWA), which converted most of the facility to become the Mid America Industrial Park.During autumn 1944, some vacant dormitories at the OOW complex were used to house German prisoners of war.  They were separated from the rest of the complex by fenced perimeters patrolled by U.S. Army military police and manned guard towers.  Prisoners were repatriated beginning in the fall of 1945.
